==English==

===Alternative spellings===
*[[dieresis]] (''especially US'')

===Noun===
'''diaeresis''' ([[diaereses]]) (''British'')

# {{orthography}}: A [[diacritic]] ( ¨ ) placed over the second of two consecutive [[vowel]]s to indicate that the second vowel is to be pronounced separately from the preceding vowel (as in ''coördinate'', a pretentious spelling of [[coordinate]], and the entirely unpretentious girls' given name of ''Zoë''. It does not indicate a [[diphthong]], but rather that each vowel has its full quality, within the sound-context. The usage is exactly the same as in the French. 

====Usage notes====
*The technical term for double-dots over a vowel is [[trema]]. The word [[umlaut]] is often substituted, but really refers to a phonological process fossilized in English mouse-mice, goose-geese and other such odd plurals, but which is still mildly active by analogy in modern German. All those dots in modern [[Turkish]] really do refer to umlaut. 

